        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "24 university students",
          "1 Advance Statistics Course",
          "Facebook Group Posts, Learner Demographics",
          "None Specified",
          "[Male, # of unclassified messages, # of messages with X (between 0 and 3 votes)]",
          "Authors use Supervise Algorithms to classify different Facebook group messages on whether they are Statistics Related on Not (Dichotomous Approach) or assigned a Relevance Ranking (Ordinal approach).\n\nStatistics-relevant messages: These Facebook posts were also coded using Bloom Taxonomy\n\n",
          "Multiple Linear Regression",
          "{RSquared: 0.496 - Model 2, Adjusted RSquared: 0.357 - Model 2}",
          "-",
          "-",
          "Classified messages are better predictors of learner performance than unclassified messages.\n\nStudents who produce fewer messages that are relevant to the course are at an increased risk of failing.\n\n",
          "Authors hypothesize that using social media information may be a relevant predictor of success in a Statistics Course.\n\nTo do that, the authors measure the messages posted in a Private Group and use Supervised ML to classify messages according to their relevance towards the course. From here, the authors create 2 Linear Regressions:\n\nModel 1: Counting number of messages in Forum\n\nModel 2: Counting number of messages in forum but splitting them according to their relevance towards the course.\n\nResults show that using ML to automate the process of classifying message relevance and subsequently using the classified messages may be a worthwhile effort.",
          "- Small sample size (24 students)\n\n- Very specific context (Facebook messages)\n\n- Does not use any additional data sources\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 3
    }
  ],
